Creating images with R

with a little bit of magick

Azzarina Azizi

2023-03-13

My meme

I used the infamous Drake meme template as a guide to create a meme that is more relatable to my life as a cat owner. I decided to take an extra step to make this meme more accurate by replacing his (Drakes) face with a cat by using the image_composite function.

library(magick)

#square one (top left)
angry_cat <- image_read("images/cat1.png") %>% 
  image_scale(600)
angry_drake <- image_read("images/drake1.jpg")
square1 <- image_border(image_scale(image_composite(angry_drake, 
                                       angry_cat, 
                                       operator = "atop", 
                                       offset = "+0+0",
                                       gravity = "northwest", 
                                       compose_args = "" ),400),
                                        "#FFFFFF", 
                                        "5x5")

#square two (top right)
square2 <- image_border(image_blank(width = 400, 
                       height = 400, 
                       color = "#000000") %>%
  image_annotate(text = "Cat toys", 
                 color = "#FFFFFF", 
                 size = 60, 
                 font = "Impact", 
                 gravity = "center"),
                  "#FFFFFF", 
                  "5x5")

#square three (bottom left)
happy_cat <- image_read("images/cat2.png") %>% image_scale(600)
happy_drake <- image_read("images/drake2.jpg")
square3 <- image_border(image_scale(image_composite(happy_drake, 
                                       happy_cat, 
                                       operator = "atop", 
                                       offset = "+400+0",
                                       gravity = "northwest", 
                                       compose_args = "" ),400),
                                        "#FFFFFF", 
                                        "5x5")

#square four (bottom right)
square4 <- image_border(image_blank(width = 400, 
                       height = 400, 
                       color = "#000000") %>%
  image_annotate(text = "The box it \ncame in", 
                 color = "#FFFFFF", 
                 size = 60, 
                 font = "Impact", 
                 gravity = "center"),
                 "#FFFFFF", 
                 "5x5")

#appending all the squares together
top_row <- image_append(c(square1, square2))
bottom_row <- image_append(c(square3, square4))

meme <- image_append(c(top_row, bottom_row), stack = TRUE)

image_write(meme, "my_meme.png")

My animated GIF

I designed the elements of this animation using an external software with simple shapes and colours to represent the simple enjoyment of my two favourite things; sunsets and cats.

#horizon for all frames
horizon <- image_blank(width = 1500, height = 350, color = "#000000")

#first frame
time1 <- image_blank(width = 200,height = 50,color="#B7B4B2") %>%
  image_annotate(text="7:00 PM", 
                 font = "Courier New",
                 color="#FFFFFF",
                 size= 30,
                 gravity = "center")

sky1 <- image_composite(image_read("images/sky.png"), 
                           time1, 
                           operator = "atop", 
                           offset = "+20+20",
                           gravity = "northwest", 
                           compose_args = "" )

sunset1 <- image_composite(sky1,
                           image_scale(image_read("images/sun.png"),
                                       600),
                           operator = "atop", 
                           offset = "+0+10",
                           gravity = "center", 
                           compose_args = "" )

frame1 <- image_append(c(sunset1, horizon), stack = TRUE)

#second frame
time2 <- image_blank(width = 200,height = 50,color="#B7B4B2") %>%
  image_annotate(text="7:15 PM", 
                 font = "Courier New",
                 color="#FFFFFF",
                 size= 30,
                 gravity = "center")

sky2 <- image_composite(image_modulate(image_read("images/sky.png"),
                                       brightness = 90,
                                       saturation = 90,
                                       hue = 490), 
                        time2, 
                        operator = "atop", 
                        offset = "+20+20",
                        gravity = "northwest", 
                        compose_args = "" )

sunset2 <- image_composite(sky2,
                           image_scale(image_read("images/sun.png"),
                                       600),
                           operator = "atop", 
                           offset = "+0+250",
                           gravity = "center", 
                           compose_args = "" )

frame2 <- image_append(c(sunset2, horizon), stack = TRUE)

#third frame
time3 <- image_blank(width = 200,height = 50,color="#B7B4B2") %>%
  image_annotate(text="7:30 PM", 
                 font = "Courier New",
                 color="#FFFFFF",
                 size= 30,
                 gravity = "center")

sky3 <- image_composite(image_modulate(image_read("images/sky.png"),
                                       brightness = 70,
                                       saturation = 80,
                                       hue = 500), 
                        time3, 
                        operator = "atop", 
                        offset = "+20+20",
                        gravity = "northwest", 
                        compose_args = "" )

sunset3 <- image_composite(sky3,
                           image_scale(image_read("images/sun.png"),
                                       600),
                           operator = "atop", 
                           offset = "+0+450",
                           gravity = "center", 
                           compose_args = "" )

frame3 <- image_append(c(sunset3, horizon), stack = TRUE)


#forth (final) frame
time4 <- image_blank(width = 200,height = 50,color="#B7B4B2") %>%
  image_annotate(text="7:45 PM", 
                 font = "Courier New",
                 color="#FFFFFF",
                 size= 30,
                 gravity = "center")

sky4 <- image_composite(image_modulate(image_read("images/sky.png"),
                                       brightness = 50,
                                       saturation = 50,
                                       hue = 700), 
                        time4, 
                        operator = "atop", 
                        offset = "+20+20",
                        gravity = "northwest", 
                        compose_args = "" )

sunset4 <- image_composite(sky4,
                           image_scale(image_read("images/sun.png"),
                                       600),
                           operator = "atop", 
                           offset = "+0+650",
                           gravity = "center", 
                           compose_args = "" )

frame4 <- image_append(c(sunset4, horizon), stack = TRUE)

#adding cat silhouttes to all the frames

cat_silhoutte <- image_read("images/cat_silhoutte.png") %>% 
  image_scale(400)

frame1_cat <- image_composite(frame1, 
                              cat_silhoutte, 
                              operator = "atop", 
                              offset = "+30+300",
                              gravity = "southeast", 
                              compose_args = "" )

frame2_cat <- image_composite(frame2, 
                              cat_silhoutte, 
                              operator = "atop", 
                              offset = "+30+300",
                              gravity = "southeast", 
                              compose_args = "" )

frame3_cat <- image_composite(frame3, 
                              cat_silhoutte, 
                              operator = "atop", 
                              offset = "+30+300",
                              gravity = "southeast", 
                              compose_args = "" )

frame4_cat <- image_composite(frame4, 
                              cat_silhoutte, 
                              operator = "atop", 
                              offset = "+30+300",
                              gravity = "southeast", 
                              compose_args = "" )

#putting all the frames together into an animation
frames <- c(frame1_cat, frame2_cat, frame3_cat, frame4_cat)
animation <- frames %>%
  image_animate(fps = 2)

image_write(animation, "my_animation.gif")
